# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Whitelist approach: ignore EVERYTHING, then allow back only the
# files worth committing. This way compiled programs, debug folders,
# and OS junk never sneak into the repo — you stay clean by default.
#
# NOTE: comments must be on their own line. A "#" after a pattern
# does NOT start a comment — it becomes part of the pattern.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 1. Ignore everything...
*

# 2. ...but still let Git look inside folders
!*/

# 3. Allow back the files you actually want tracked.

# C++ source and headers
!*.cpp
!*.h
!*.hpp
!*.cc

# Data files your programs read
!*.txt
!*.csv
!*.dat

# Notes / README and this ignore file itself
!*.md
!.gitignore

gradeData.txt